AU  - MALLOY, CHRISTOPHER
AU  - POMORSKI, LUKASZ
Y1  - 2012/06/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01740.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1009
EP  - 1043
VL  - 67
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01740.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Exploiting the fact that insiders trade for a variety of reasons, we show that there is predictable, identifiable ?routine? insider trading that is not informative about firms? futures. A portfolio strategy that focuses solely on the remaining ?opportunistic? traders yields value-weighted abnormal returns of 82 basis points per month, while abnormal returns associated with routine traders are essentially zero. The most informed opportunistic traders are local, nonexecutive insiders from geographically concentrated, poorly governed firms. Opportunistic traders are significantly more likely to have SEC enforcement action taken against them, and reduce trading following waves of SEC insider trading enforcement.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Determinants of Cross-Border Mergers and Acquisitions
AU  - EREL, ISIL
AU  - LIAO, ROSE C.
AU  - WEISBACH, MICHAEL S.
Y1  - 2012/06/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01741.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1045
EP  - 1082
VL  - 67
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01741.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT The vast majority of cross-border mergers involve private firms outside of the United States. We analyze a sample of 56,978 cross-border mergers between 1990 and 2007. We find that geography, the quality of accounting disclosure, and bilateral trade increase the likelihood of mergers between two countries. Valuation appears to play a role in motivating mergers: firms in countries whose stock market has increased in value, whose currency has recently appreciated, and that have a relatively high market-to-book value tend to be purchasers, while firms from weaker-performing economies tend to be targets.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Threshold Events and Identification: A Study of Cash Shortfalls
AU  - BAKKE, TOR-ERIK
AU  - WHITED, TONI M.
Y1  - 2012/06/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01742.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1083
EP  - 1111
VL  - 67
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01742.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Threshold events are discrete events triggered when an observable continuous variable passes a known threshold. We demonstrate how to use threshold events as identification strategies by revisiting the evidence in Rauh (2006, Investment and financing constraints: Evidence from the funding of corporate pension plans, Journal of Finance 61, 33?71) that mandatory pension contributions cause investment declines. Rauh's result stems from heavily underfunded firms that constitute a small fraction of the sample and that differ sharply from the rest of the sample. To alleviate this issue, we use observations near funding thresholds and find causal effects of mandatory contributions on receivables, R&D, and hiring, but not on investment. We also provide useful suggestions and diagnostics for analyzing threshold events.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Investment, Idiosyncratic Risk, and Ownership
AU  - PANOUSI, VASIA
AU  - PAPANIKOLAOU, DIMITRIS
Y1  - 2012/06/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01743.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1113
EP  - 1148
VL  - 67
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01743.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT High-powered incentives may induce higher managerial effort, but they also expose managers to idiosyncratic risk. If managers are risk averse, they might underinvest when firm-specific uncertainty increases, leading to suboptimal investment decisions from the perspective of well-diversified shareholders. We empirically document that, when idiosyncratic risk rises, firm investment falls, and more so when managers own a larger fraction of the firm. This negative effect of managerial risk aversion on investment is mitigated if executives are compensated with options rather than with shares or if institutional investors form a large part of the shareholder base.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - CEO Compensation and Board Structure Revisited
AU  - GUTHRIE, KATHERINE
AU  - SOKOLOWSKY, JAN
AU  - WAN, KAM-MING
Y1  - 2012/06/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/06/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01744.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 1149
EP  - 1168
VL  - 67
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2012.01744.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Chhaochharia and Grinstein estimate that CEO pay decreases 17% more in firms that were not compliant with the recent NYSE/Nasdaq board independence requirement than in firms that were compliant. We document that 74% of this magnitude is attributable to two outliers of 865 sample firms. In addition, we find that the compensation committee independence requirement increases CEO total pay, particularly in the presence of effective shareholder monitoring. Our evidence casts doubt on the effectiveness of independent directors in constraining CEO pay as suggested by the managerial power hypothesis.
ER  - 

